0":"1100","1066":"1066","after 1130":"na 1130","before 1142":"vóór 1142","1142":"1142","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1173":"1173","21 September 1173":"21 september 1173","1209":"1209","1070":"1070","Okehampton, Kent, England":"Kent, England","Okehampton, Devon, England":"Okehampton, Devon, England"},"en":{"–21 September 1173":"–21 September 1173","–1173":"–1173","1100–1142":"1100–1142","–1209":"–1209","1070–Male":"1070–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","after 1130":"after 1130","before 1142":"before 1142","1142":"1142","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1173":"1173","21 September 1173":"21 September 1173","1209":"1209","1070":"1070","Okehampton, Kent, England":"Kent, England","Okehampton, Devon, England":"Okehampton, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Avenell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Old French personal name <i>Avenel</i>, a double diminutive of ancient Germanic <i>Avo</i>. The surname was later confused with   Averill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Averill","meanings":["English:","apparently from the name of the month (April), Middle English <i>averil</i>, Old French <i>avrill</i>, Latin <i>aprīlis</i>, perhaps with reference to freshness of temperament, or youth, or possibly to the changeable weather of the month.","perhaps occasionally a habitational name from Haverhill in Suffolk, with loss of initial <i>H-</i>. The placename derives from either Old English <i>hæfera</i> ‘oats’ or <i>hæfer</i> ‘he-goat’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Avery  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":12,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":32,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.go